04124nam a22005655i 9780300145090DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20082008ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001450907 a10.12987/97803001450902doi  a(DE-B1597)484857  a(OCoLC)994599898  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aHQ759.48b.G55 2008eb 7aSOC0280002bisacsh04a306.874/32221 aGilbert, Neil, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Mother's Work :bHow Feminism, the Market, and Policy Shape Family Life /cNeil Gilbert. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b6 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tI. Responding to the Tensions of Work and Family -- tII. Capitalism, Feminism, and the Family-Friendly State -- tConclusion: An Alternative to the Male Model -- tAppendix: Data on Factors Related to Fertility -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe question of how best to combine work and family life has led to lively debates in recent years. Both a lifestyle and a policy issue, it has been addressed psychologically, socially, and economically, and conclusions have been hotly contested. But as Neil Gilbert shows in this penetrating and provocative book, we haven't looked closely enough at how and why these questions are framed, or who benefits from the proposed answers.A Mother's Work takes a hard look at the unprecedented rise in childlessness, along with the outsourcing of family care and household production, which have helped to alter family life since the 1960s. It challenges the conventional view on how to balance motherhood and employment, and examines how the choices women make are influenced by the culture of capitalism, feminist expectations, and the social policies of the welfare state. Gilbert argues that while the market ignores the essential value of a mother's work, prevailing norms about the social benefits of work have been overvalued by elites whose opportunities and circumstances little resemble those of most working- and middle-class mothers. And the policies that have been crafted too often seem friendlier to the market than to the family. Gilbert ends his discussion by looking at the issue internationally, and he makes the case for reframing the debate to include a wider range of social values and public benefits that present more options for managing work and family responsibilities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aFamily policyxUnited States. 0aFeminist theoryxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aWomen in the professionsxUnited States. 0aWork and familyxUnited States. 0aWorking mothersxUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300145090423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300145090.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles